AB  - As it is well known, images, both verbal and pictorial, are not always
met with delight and they are certainly not appreciated by all. They
are also perceived as threatening and the first to come to mind as
being afraid of images are undeniably jurists. Jurists fear images
foremost and by vocation. After all, they are expected to establish
order, a mission they see frequently challenged by the ambiguity of
images. For, as long as it is not possible to ascribe to images a
monosemic pictorial content, they will not be fit to provide a
foundation capable of sustaining order. Polisemic images do not
achieve an emblematic effect nor do they suggest any binding,
order-establishing force. They proliferate, they are up to mischief in
the fantasmatic, and they all of a sudden attack order structures that
may have been intact for centuries. So it is hardly surprising if in
the context of ‘image and law’ what is striking is the misalliance
between the two, a troubled relationship, as it were, due to the
pronounced image scepticism on behalf of jurists.
