AB  - Based on quantitative data, this article investigates the use of legal
iconography in Icelandic law manuscripts produced in c. 1330–1600,
focusing primarily on manuscripts of two important vernacular legal
codes: Jónsbók from 1281 and Kristinréttr Árna Þorlákssonar from 1275.
The article is divided into three sections: the first section provides
a short historical introduction to the establishment of the vernacular
Icelandic law codes in the Middle Ages. Based on this textual
background, the second section describes the appearance of
text-related book painting that accompanies these law codes in the
manuscripts. The third section concludes the article and elaborates
further on the intentions behind the use of text-related book
painting.
