AB  - Abstract The Madras High Court located in Chennai, India, was
established in 1862 when India was under colonial rule. It continues
to exist in post-independence India after merging into the Indian
legal system. In this study, I argue that the architecture and
judicial iconography of the Madras High Court building reflects a
recurring historical tension between Indian and British concepts of
justice. This is continually reflected in the semiotics of the legal
space of this high court which in turn influences the legal
consciousness of the court personnel who utilize this space. This
architecture and iconography of the Madras High Court constitutes,
preserves, and reinforces the ambivalent legal consciousness of those
who created, occupy, and visit this space. The contemporary legal
consciousness of the court personnel is thus seen to have deep
historical roots.
