AB  - In the general introduction to this contributed volume of selected
conference proceedings, the title ‘The Art of Law’ is explained,
particularly by situating the Bruges interdisciplinary conference in
the ‘Arts and Humanities’ movement. A short overview of the status
quaestionis of historical legal iconology is given, and suggestions
are made on how art historians and legal historians can collaborate in
a field of research that is very attractive for both disciplines. This
introductory paper also identifies some methodological and material
links between the various contributions to the volume.
