AB  - Over the centuries, European debate about the nature and status of
images of God and sacred figures has often upset the established order
and shaken societies to their core. Out of this debate, an
identifiable doctrine has emerged of the image in general and of the
divine image in particular. This fascinating work concentrates on
these historical arguments, from the period of Late Antiquity up to
the great and classic defenses of images by St. John of Damascus and
Theodore of Studion. Icon extends beyond the immediate concerns of
religion, philosophy, aesthetics, history, and art, to engage them
all.
