AB  - Abstract The article analyses the title page of Vico’s New Science in
light of Hiroshi Sugimoto’s series Theaters and the emblematic of
Goodrich and Legendre, showing how the rhetorical tradition of Italian
legal humanism and the Japanese visual culture conceive a vision of
Law and Humanities that opposes Cartesian rationalism and the
logocentrism of contemporary legal positivism. Visual legal studies
question the perspective in painting, theater and cinema, and its
cultural and political implications at the time of the media
revolution and the emergence of the normativity of the image.
