AB  - The icon and the word are different types of signs, but they have in
common the capacity to portray. Thus the term 'portrait' has long been
used to refer both to visible representations of things, especially to
delineations of the human face, and to verbal descriptions of things
or persons. We get some sense of what it means to portray by recalling
that the word's Latin source, protrahere, means to draw out or pull
out something, to reveal the thing by bringing it into the open or
into the light. Portraiture, whether visual or verbal, brings an
object to presence for us by making its features stand out from what
might otherwise hide or obscure them. In portraits of human beings,
these hidden features typically refer to character, which is generally
understood as some essential aspect of a person valid throughout his
life (Steiner 1977: 114). Yet what may we say about the case where the
same person is portrayed by both pictures and words? Can iconic and
verbal signs have an identical or even a congruent signification,
especially where the subject of portraiture is something as elusive as
the person's character? Some have indicated that the differences in
iconic and verbal portraits of a person must far outweigh any
similarities that exist between them. McLuhan (1965) suggests this,
for example, in his comparision of verbal and iconic communication. By
McLuhan's account, modern civilization in the West derived its
original qualities from the development of printing and the spread of
literacy. With the invention of photography and television, however,
the image came to supplant the written word as the
