AB  - Abstract The role played by pictures in the formation of our legal
imaginations is one that has attracted the attention of socio‐legal
scholars. Research in this field is on the rise and diversifying.
However, to date there has been little engagement with, or reflection
on, the methods and methodology that researchers have deployed in
their turn to pictures as data. The goal of this article is to explore
a range of methodological issues by way of several different types of
pictures: paintings, photographs, and moving pictures with sound
generated by way of lens‐based digital technologies.
