AB  - This article discusses how law is produced semiotically as a category
of social action through a study of jury decision making and the
production of jury verdicts. In the US criminal justice system,
citizens called for jury duty are interpellated as jurors and
instructed in legal reasoning through encounters with a variety of
texts. Jurors respond to the state’s hailing by producing themselves
as competent jurors who can reason according to specifically legal
forms of objectivity that may diverge from their everyday assessments
of facts in reaching verdicts: for example, they can find a defendant
legally “not guilty” while maintaining a belief in the defendant’s
guilt. In ethnographic data discussed in this article, jurors affirm
their competence as legal reasoners via the “enregisterment” of a
style of reasoning that they link indexically to the constitutionally
enshrined ideal of “impartiality.” In so doing, jurors recontextualize
a style of reasoning, grounded in a logic of a “moralized objectivity
of self-restraint” (Daston and Galison 1992), entextualized in the
texts used to instruct them in legal reasoning during the trial
process. Tracing these processes of enregisterment illustrates how
legitimacy of law is semiotically mediated.
