AB  - The connection between law and music is intuitive, but difficult to
explain. The argument offered by this paper is that music supplies a
set of images that law, given its limited lexicon, lacks. Music, in
this view, is a cognitive metaphor which allows legal science to use
one conceptual domain (music) to reason about another (law). This was
the case in 16th century discussions of judicial equity in France. The
distrust of judicial discretion pushed to the currency of powerful
images of decision-making expressed in musical-mathematical terms.
