AB  - Applying the ideas of Edward Said about orientalism and the
relationship between colonialism and culture, we discuss the
eurocentric opposition between the Western "I" and the Oriental
"Other". We analyze works by European painters from the 19th century
using both the compared and iconological methods to highlight the
marginality of some images and the centrality of others. We show that
such representations are also found in Western law, which acts as a
discourse of the colonial power that is felt at the metropolis and at
the periphery, a discourse that still lives today and still finds
resistance and opposition.
