AB  - Examining the intellectual, cultural, and social implications of
reading visual and bodily manifestations as signs of guilt and
innocence means grappling with the relationship between what is true
and what is credible, and consequently with the problem of how to make
judgments when lacking absolute certainty. This essay explores this
problem by focusing on the afterlife of Augustine's notion of
credulitas, or “belief,” in two parallel but intertwined areas: moral
theology and legal thought. In both cases, absolute certainty was the
gold standard against which moral actions and legal judgments were
traditionally held. Yet moral theologians and legal scholars knew that
sometimes absolute certainty was impossible to reach, so how could
they form decisions that were both epistemologically correct and
morally safe? The answers that theologians and jurists gave were
different, and yet they were linked with and responded to each other
in complex and interesting ways.
