AB  - The article attempts to highlight the complex of problems associated
with the establishment of the right of last confession for criminal
offenders in France at the end of the 14th century. The author’s main
attention is focused on two works written by French intellectuals:
Philippe de Mézières’s Le songe du vieil pelerine (1389) and Jean
Gerson’s Requete pour les condamnés à mort (1395/1396). The analysis
of the circumstances of the creation of these texts, of their internal
structure and the argumentation contained in them allows to answer the
question why the proposal of J. Gerson was positively received at the
court of Charles VI, while the similar efforts of Ph. de Mézières
failed. The author of the article connects this paradox with the
political climate in France (primarily at the royal court) that has
changed in just a few years, with the reform of the judicial system,
which has been going on with more or less success during these years.
However, the most significant circumstance, according to the author of
the article, was Jean Gerson’s extremely balanced position on the
relationship between secular authorities and the Church in such a
controversial issue as criminal procedure law. The author also links
the changes that took place in the 15th century in the general
iconography of French chronicles and historical writings to changes in
this area: already in the first half of the century, artists began to
regularly depict priests listening to the last confession of criminals
in execution scenes. Thus, the article touches on one of the most
controversial issues of modern medieval studies - the iconographic
turn in the history of law.
