AB  - The Bombay High Court in Mumbai was constructed in 1878 and has its
own unique judicial iconography. This contribution investigates the
visual narrative of the High Court by analysing the statues of justice
and mercy that are placed atop the High Court building, the carvings
of the ‘monkey judge’ and ‘fox lawyer’ on the pillars of the court,
and several other visual representations of justice. The iconography
has played a role in the development of popular cultural imagery, and
has its own folklore in the court today. This paper is an attempt to
document the court in terms of its visual representation and the
survival thereof in a colonial construction that is now part of
independent India.
