AB  - This latest volume in the Garland Medieval Bibliographies series
follows other valuable source books such as Eileen Gardiner, ed.,
Medieval Visions of Heaven and Hell: A Sourcebook (New York: Garland,
1993); Margaret L. Switten, ed., Music and Poetry in the Middle Ages
(New York: Garland, 1995); Maryjane Dunn and Linda Kay Davidson, The
Pilgrimage to Santiago de Compostela, (New York: Garland, 1994); and
Susan E. Farrier, The Medieval Charlemagne Legend: An Annotated
Bibliography (New York: Garland, 1993). The authors believe that there
exists "no book in English quite like" this one, which "aims to help
the researcher locate visual motifs, whether in medieval art or in
literature, and to understand how they function in yet other medieval
literary or artistic works" (ix). This guide is intended for the
advanced undergraduate, the graduate student, or the literary scholar
challenged by a complex visual idea. Divided into two main sections,
the Guide first treats tools, and then themes in both learned and
popular culture. Chapter 1, "Art," is the longest (one hundred pages),
and includes general reference works as well as particular sources,
divided by topic (for example, "Ivory," "Monumental Art by Country,"
"Wood-Carving"). The second chapter includes "other tools" as sources
of imagery: encyclopedias, sermon collections, and exempla. Part 2
allots a chapter each to "Learned Imagery," "The Christian Tradition,"
"The Natural World," and "Medieval Daily Life." This reviewer noticed
two errors: "le peche originel" instead of "peche" (218), and
"tympannum" instead of "tympanum" (410). This excellent guide
complements more discursive works like Helene E. Roberts, ed., The
Encyclopedia of Comparative Iconography: Themes Depicted in Works of
Art (Chicago: Fitzroy Dearborn Publishers, 1998), and provides a rich
interdisciplinary resource for the medievalist.
