AB  - This study aims to examine how Project 2025’s blueprint for
dismantling democratic institutions exemplifies symbolic governance -
the maintenance of legal forms while systematically excluding
participation and accountability. Using Puerto Rico’s territorial
subordination and Project 2025’s proposed civil service purges as case
studies, this research reframes legality as a potential mask for
authoritarian consolidation rather than a guarantee of justice.

This study applies normative-philosophical framework (Dworkin, Fuller,
Fraser) to Puerto Rico and Project 2025 case studies, supplemented by
World Values Survey data with ordinal logistic regression testing
correlations between institutional trust and perceived political
legitimacy.

Symbolic legality enables institutions to simulate legitimacy while
suppressing justice, as demonstrated through Puerto Rico’s territorial
subordination and Project 2025’s formalization of authoritarianism.
Trust in courts correlates with democratic legitimacy, while trust in
police correlates with disillusionment, revealing bifurcated
legitimacy.

Limited to cross-sectional data and specific political contexts,
broader generalization requires comparative cross-national research.
Framework provides foundation for analyzing ethical pathologies of
legal institutions.

This study recommends evaluating legal institutions by ethical
integrity, not just procedural metrics. This study proposes reforms
emphasizing epistemic inclusion, participatory justice and legal
intelligibility in postcolonial and fragile democratic contexts.

Institutional denial corrodes democratic accountability even in
societies priding themselves on legal order. This study calls for
reimagining law’s role in advancing justice rather than performing
compliance.

This study bridges legal philosophy, political theory and empirical
social science to introduce symbolic governance as ethical pathology.
It offers new normative vocabulary for analyzing legal systems under
moral strain.
