AB  - In the 12th — 13th centuries, 14 texts of the local urban law were
created in Freiburg im Breisgau. Of these, 8 have introductory
sections, and 7 have concluding sections. These introductions and
conclusions contain, among other things, crucial information
concerning dating. This dating pertains, on the one hand, to the
creation of the texts themselves and, on the other hand, to a specific
event in the town’s history that prompted the drafting of the legal
document; in one instance, it also refers to an event in local history
that lies at a considerable temporal distance from the moment of the
source’s creation. The Freiburg legislators employ the image of time
as historical memory, pointing to significant events and well-known
figures from Freiburg’s history, exemplary legislation, and, most
importantly, defining the orientation of the local laws “towards the
future”, thereby establishing a firm connection between past, present,
and future within the local legal framework. One text stands out, the
compiler of which demonstrates the particular view on the passage of
time by merging into a single whole the concepts of linear and
circular (cyclical) time. All of this “imagery” of time serves the
legislators’ primary goal which is to lend the municipal law greater
significance and weight.
