AB  - For scholars of religion, philosophy, and the history of art (but,
regrettably, not of the history of rhetoric), there has been no
shortage of studies devoted to Byzantine Iconoclasm, the period during
which the very concept of the image was thrown into question. That
period brokered an end to late antiquity and inaugurated a Christian
“Orthodox” visual culture. Iconoclasm is typically bookended by the
event of the emperor Leo III’s decision to take down Christ’s image
from the Chalke Gate in 726 and Patriarch Photius’s sermon on the
mosaic of the Virgin and Child in Hagia Sophia in 867. Scholars mostly
agree that not many images were actually destroyed but, rather, a
complex discourse emerged revolving around the problem of defining and
venerating sacred images. These discourses were fiercely polemical.
One group would charge the other with idolatry and paganism: for
example, the iconoclast emperor Constantine V (718–75 CE) defined
painting as a “vulgar Hellenic art” (Gero 1977, 86).The other group
would respond with a countercharge of desecration of Christian custom
as handed down by Scripture and the fathers. For the defenders of
images, one of the scapegoats was the Jew, the prototypical
iconoclast. Despite the rhetorical importance of that figure, the
rhetorical value of the image in Jewish Rabbinic writing during the
period leading up to the crisis has, so far, not entered any
discussion of the image in the Mediterranean world. Nearly all
discourses have focused entirely on Christ and the struggles to define
a Christian visual culture. Alexei Sivertsev corrects this oversight
and in an extraordinary book demonstrates the riches that Jewish
literature has to offer on modes of conceiving divinity in late
antiquity. Like their Christian neighbors, Jewish writers were
addressing the same difficulties about their religious inheritance.By
reading Hebrew liturgical poetry (piyyutim) and mystical texts
alongside Christian writers such as Pseudo-Dionysius, Cyril of
Alexandria, and Maximos the Confessor, Jews, Christians, and the
Discourse on Images before Iconoclasm expands the understanding of the
image in Mediterranean culture. Jewish tradition is not simply a
support or a shadow to a teleological culmination in Christian
enunciations of Platonic modes of argumentation regarding
representation set forth by theologians like John of Damascus, that
is, modes of argument that involved images and their truth capacity
and revolved around likenesses and prototypes as they came to bear on
what we recognize today as the Christian portrait icon. Instead, the
focus centers on the profound nuance with which Jewish writers
addressed specific problems, such as how a mortal body could be both
heavenly and earthly or how the shapeless God could condescend to
spatial, that is, architectural containment.Sivertsev follows Roland
Barthes, who defines discourse as “a horizon, which implies both a
boundary and a perspective” (3). Therefore, the chapters of Jews,
Christians, and the Discourse on Images before Iconoclasm do not
unfold following a singular line of argument, except the claim that
the category of image allowed both Jews and Christians to
conceptualize the divine in relation to certain figural bounds.
Rather, Sivertsev’s approach—and, indeed, what makes this book a
pleasure to read—is that the chapters focus on certain figures or
image gestalts within discourse that travel across religious
boundaries. An example of such a gestalt is that, both in the poet
Yannai’s rhetorical figure of Israel and the Christian theologian
Maximus the Confessor’s definition of liturgical mystagogy, the idea
that a ritual mass “resembling God” opens the possibility “for the
radically transcendental God to be reinvited within a spatially
delineated mode of existence” (49). The nature of divine transcendence
and condescension is a problem, no doubt, for the late antique Jewish
and Christian writers, just as it was during the later debates in
Constantinople. But what Sivertsev draws our attention to is the
resemblances between two faith traditions in thinking through
rhetorical possibilities rather than determining fixed rules about
representation. This new body of material and set of comparisons is a
truly welcome addition to the body of writing devoted to theories of
the visual in premodern religions writ large. For scholars of
rhetoric, both Sivertsev’s sources and his analyses will enhance
current understandings of late antique thought about language’s
ability to compete with or to engage visual material.Chapter 1 begins
with the poet Yannai’s use of the word image in relation to liturgical
community and to the idea of “dissimilar similarity.” Drawing on the
Christian Neoplatonist Pseudo-Dionysius, Sivertsev examines a
rhetorical figure of image as “the space in which one sign system is
transcribed by means of another” (27). This tracks onto Yannai’s
paradigm for the image as the collective of the people of Israel:
“Israel’s status as the unique people becomes the only means of
placing God’s nonreferential being within a referencing system that
would make God epistemically recognizable to human gaze” (48). The
collective body Israel, then, becomes a form, a possibility through
which God’s uniqueness is revealed and predicated on a paradigm of
mirroring. Sivertsev tracks similarities between the ritual collective
as image within the Mystagogy of Maximos the Confessor. What emerges
is a shared rhetoric of mirroring, chiasm, and prototype in which
divine ineffability gets recoded into different figurations of
liturgical community.Chapter 2 focuses on the history of Jacob’s
image, beginning in the fifth century with the motif’s appearance in
midrashic anthologies such as the Lamentations Rabbah and the Genesis
Rabbah. The image is that of Jacob engraved on the throne of God. The
phenomenon was imagined also in Yannai’s poetry as well as the
mystical collection known as Hekhalot rabbatti. Sivertsev examines the
Jacob image in relation to Christian thinkers such as Maximus the
Confessor. He then compares the subsequent imagining of Jacob’s image
on the throne with presentations of Saint Demetrius. At stake in this
chapter is how both Christian and Jewish writers in late antiquity
were discursively upholding the sacred body to understand God and
human isomorphism. One of the strengths of this chapter is drawing out
the commonalities in late antiquity between Christian and Jewish forms
of image veneration revolving around the practice of votives.Chapter 3
focuses on the paradigm of how Jacob’s sleeping body (Genesis 28) and
the image of Jacob inscribed on the throne open a spatial field. In
the paradigm, “the audience is invited to experience the two bodies in
the act of cross-referential viewing” (108). As Sivertsev explores,
this simultaneously earthly and heavenly presence is also a
preoccupation for Christian treatments of saints’ images: the
verticality between the historical cross and an image of Christ’s face
on a pilgrim’s object is evidence for Sivertsev that late antique
Christians were participating in a similarly “cross-referential
viewing” of material and divine bodies. If I understand the argument
here, the paradigm grounding the comparison is the construction of a
spatial field in which earthly and divine bodies become known.In the
same chapter, Sivertsev writes: “Instead of suggesting a direct
relationship between the two traditions, however, I would like to view
them as two configurations of an idiom independently realized with the
parameters of the common horizon of possibilities, or in Gombrich’s
words, as two faithful constructions of a relational model” (107).
This sentence is an example simultaneously of Sivertsev’s extremely
rigorous thought but also its often-obscure presentation. The reader
is left unsure. Are we talking about comparison, and, if so, on what
grounds? At stake in the chapter are two orientations or schemes of
space—a real and an imagined body for a sacred persona in late
antiquity—but what has the one to do with Sivertsev’s framing, which
seems to present two separate matrices that self-multiply? Could
Sivertsev simply have said that verticality was a common means of
facing the shared late antique problem of relic presence and the
saint’s invisible existence in heaven? I admit that the spatial
gestalt or “formula” becomes a bit difficult to follow because, to my
mind, we are not quite discussing the category of image as something
static.That said, chapters 3 and 4 feel a bit more grounded in objects
and materials. God’s self-contraction or shrinking (tzimtzum) into the
tabernacle structures a marvelous cross-cultural analysis with the
same phenomenon of Byzantine imaginings of architecture, which
represents the body of Mary, the Mother of God, as “wider than the
Heavens” (158) for having borne the divinity in her womb. Chapter 4
coheres around the rhetorical question, How could the uncontainable be
contained? Works of Rabbinic literature such as the Genesis Rabbah and
Pesqita of Rav Kahana are juxtaposed to writings by Christian authors
such as Cyril of Alexandria and Romanos the Melodist, Constantinople’s
liturgical poet. Sivertsev draws some compelling contrasts:
rhetorically articulated conceptions of containing the divine energy
led to feminine imagery in Christian thought, materializing in figures
such as the Virgin Mary’s body or the ecclesia, the church space
itself. By contrast, the symbolic vocabulary found in Jewish texts
focuses on divine circumscription in relation to the tabernacle.
Furthermore, the paradox of the Incarnation—so central to Christian
belief—finds no envisioning in late antique Jewish understandings of
the tabernacle.The problem of the “impossible” nature of the divine as
it relates to interiors, light and color, and objects themselves
grounds chapter 4. Similar themes from earlier chapters, such as
conceptions of divine immanence in the terms of likeness and
resemblance, come to
