AB  - «Images of Justice in the Aesthetics of the Law». Political philosophy
must analyze not only the concepts and texts of the canon but also
metaphors and artistic representations. This article examines how the
images of Justice historically have changed from ancient Mesopotamia
to the present day. Focusing on the question of Justice’s blindness or
being clear-sighted, the article points out eight iconographic
traditions that have expressed various ways of answering the question:
Should Justice possess an unlimited sight that penetrates even the
heart of human beings or should she be blind to treat all people
equally?
