AB  - The thirty six miniatures of the Gratian Decree kept by the municipal
library of Avignon (ms 659, Toulouse, XIVth century) give an
exceptionnal role to the ecclesiastical judge, even compared with the
standards set by the illustration of Toulousan manuscripts, which
alrea¬ dy give him the lion’s share (I). On the opposite, the
supplicant, the petitioner and the opponent are representated in a
modest position which does not square with their role in the text
(II). At last, even more oddly, the representative in justice
dominates the audience with the judge. He develops vigorously a
clever, even scholarly, address to the Court (III). The prestige of
this graduate in law and the place devoted to the written document
(roll, book) are characteristic of the Southern French society.
