AB  - Conjured in the main during the sequestration of the pandemic, Law and
Film is a dramatic, acute, yet convivial intervention into an
expanding field of jurisprudential interest. It is a skillfully
curated collection of essays on the impact of film on legal theory,
developed out of a desire to enjoy film and to use it as a conduit for
existential, theoretical, and pedagogic revitalization of the jurist's
relation to and inhabitation of both doctrine and practice. While
‘Eating Popcorn Like a Lawyer’, the title of the orienting essay by
the editors, might sound flip or cognitively thin, it in fact captures
the first major theme of the volume, which is that of using film –
understood here as any streamed visual narrative in our era, as
Gabriele Pedullà puts it, ‘after the cinema’,1 and also as the
collective experience and visceral enjoyment of watching and
dissecting specific movies – to bring legal abstraction down to earth.
Precisely because the pandemic separated and virtualized the
experience of studying law, it proliferated a shift towards a new
materialism, and here a drive to reimagine the academic experience,
and to reinvigorate embodied performance, the corporeal enactment of
the scholarly, pedagogic, official, and social dimensions of learning
and writing about the juridical realm that jurists inhabit. The
opening opens to affect in a dual sense. It starts with a
dissatisfaction, an unease that is often felt in the process of
becoming a ‘lawyer academical’, focusing on what is lost or left
behind in taking up the mantle and role of reproducing legal
institutions. Particularly during a pandemic shutdown, the study of
law seems dead, monochrome, the epitome of what Friedrich Nietzsche
describes as a profession of filing clerks lost in the dust of
archives and the dead letters of arcane texts.2 The turn to film, to
eating popcorn, unabashedly seeks to inject enjoyment into the process
of study and to reimagine both reality and law through the fictions on
screen. The boredom of reading and writing about law estranges the
scholar from the reality of law, the contexts of its performances, and
the body that incorporates and enacts it. Reduced simply to text – to
‘black letters’, as the expression was – law is not only a source of
ennui but also of estrangement from feeling, a disembodiment that is
boring in the negative sense of passivity, lassitude, and lack of
critical focus. The opaque language, the abstraction, and the lack of
images and colours dull apprehension, and suppress the anxieties and
doubts that question and potentially motivate critique of the violence
and inequality that the abstraction of rules tends to cloak and hide.
Movies, clips, and images, the argument for law and film contends, can
revitalize, invigorate, engage, and transmit a visceral relation and
affective response to the sedimented dogmatics embedded in
disciplinary reproduction. The initial sense of film as an antidote –
as dispelling boredom and rescuing the jurist who has become in one
phrase a wandering, though no longer wondering, encyclopedia – is that
of a critical corrective. Film is a vehicle for enjoyment that will
provide access to other ideas, to the felt sense of seeking to do
justice. The argument is refreshing, not least in admitting that as
pedants – academics, scholars, jurists – we seek to enjoy law as a
modality and object of study, and to believe that betterment may be
promoted through our scholarly work. It is this impulse, this desire,
so often denied in legal studies, for the hermeneutic and didactic
jouissance of erudition that propels several of the essays and perhaps
most distinctively the excursus into existentialism and its roots in
Nietzsche's philosophy undertaken in Louis Hill's ‘Revitalising the
Law’. The theme that Hill climbs is that of method as existence,
posing insistently the question of the impact of cinema on the
everyday lives of legal scholars. How do they inhabit their roles
differently as a result of enjoying their work more? The answer is
that film grounds, contextualizes, connects, and engages the jurist in
a dialogue with experience that responds to the environments and
material occasions of law's transmission and subjective hold on its
subjects. For law to change, the lawyer has to reform, feel, and
commit, and film can help in that essentially therapeutic process. The
most compelling analysis of the existential quandary and political
dilemma of the critical legal neophyte comes in a savage essay by
Alberto Rinaldi, dissecting Abel Ferrara's 1995 movie The Addiction.
Taking off from Walter Benjamin's essay on the critique of violence3
and addressing the effects of writing about evil in the context of the
horrors that have to be witnessed by scholars of international law,
Rinaldi uses the movie as a device to analyse the narcotic effects of
legal academic literature. The protagonist of the film, a PhD student,
is bitten by, and so becomes, a vampire. A different perspective on
the academy emerges, in which the scholar of international law is
portrayed through the vampiric lens as slowly falling into addiction:
‘A slave to your cravings, a vampire in search of other disciplines to
bleed out’ (p. 30). The academic as addict uses scholarship, writing,
both as a device for building a persona – we are what we write – and
as an escape route from the world and from feeling the impact of law;
‘[a] screen is placed between us and the evil we attempt to describe
and make sense of’ through dissertation, monograph, and article (p.
24). The critical point is that ‘[a]cademics just go on as if nothing
mattered, as if everything was normal’ (p. 28). Over time and
producing the comfortable screeds, the publications that advance a
career, the figure of the vampire coalesces in the academic's
scriptive addiction, the escape route of writing, and thus we become
‘part of that evil we keep describing so clinically and naturally … We
have embarked upon a journey with no return … [i]mmolated on the altar
of the academic abattoir’ (p. 38). The left critique of academic
international law is not in itself especially novel. The point that
this genre of scholarship is self-serving and evades the questions
thrown up by international events and conflict is made very forcefully
by long-serving scholars such as Anthony Carty and Pierre Legrand, and
by younger advocates such as Robert Knox and Helena Alviar García (the
latter also among the contributors to this volume).4 What is
distinctive is the use of film to carry a more visceral argument and
sensibility, a force and passion that escapes the conventions of
semiotics through accessing the road to a libidinal economy. The
medium of film refuses the mise en signe, which reduces, substitutes,
and enmeshes the sign in nihilism, remaining in semiotic thought,
which is – to borrow from Jean-François Lyotard – ‘to languish in
religious melancholy and to subordinate every intense emotion to a
lack and every force to finitude’.5 Escape, liberation from
academicism and its semiotics, is to dispel boredom, to have fun, to
choose acturience and access reality – as Vittoria Becci formulates it
– through film and its multi-sensory versions of fictions, both legal
and narrative (p. 5). The other dimension of escaping boredom and its
stupefaction is to embrace the boring, the drilling down to something
creative and cognitively interesting. As Rinaldi points out, and as
his postdoctoral position indicates, joining the academy involves
exchange, institution and office, and modes of compromise. Film as
fun, eating popcorn as a lawyer, is transformative, and – to borrow
from another recent work on the topic – it is through movies that ‘the
dry as dust soil of legal doctrine flowers into something truly
substantive and dramatically compelling’.6 That long-resisted theme of
affect in law, forever a minor language of comedy in its old sense of
theatrical genre, is reinstated as a valued method of propaedeutics
and also as an existential carapace that enables critical performance
and an authenticity of lifestyle and inhabitation of office. What is
key is that film is recognized in this collection as a hedonic
strategy, a medium of legal transmission that engages the jouissance
of theory and the libidinal economy of the imaginal relay through
which most subjects first and most often encounter matters legal. The
latter point propels the second feature of affect: the aligned sense
in which image, clip, and film gain legal gravitas and epistemic
status as a result of the remediated transfer of legal norms and
policies. The editors write of replacing thinking like a lawyer with
eating like a lawyer, as a means of shifting ‘from the mind to the
body and the personal’ (p. 3), suggesting the interior intimacy of
thought, as well as the physical community of scholarship and seminar.
This is not to suggest an antinomy but rather an imbrication and
commonality that recognizes the appeal of the imagetic because, as
Hill puts it, ‘movies impress images on us that we cannot escape’ (p.
147) and, as Rinaldi also observes, those pictures haunt and infest
the several world of the night. To take the obvious starting point, it
is through the myriad filmic, televisual, and streamed legal dramas,
courtroom scenes, enforcement mysteries, thrillers, and now also
streamed court hearings, proposed as recently as January 2025 in the
UK ‘Call for Evidence: Open Justice, the Way Forward – Summary of
Responses’,7 that the student first encounters and primarily follows
the rule and concept of law. This novel medium or more accurately
remediation of law juxtaposes the image and enactment of the juridical
with the now seemingly outdated pedagogy of the exegetical and
textual. The field, as the editors note, is now in motion and
performance is law. How does remediation impact the classical trinity
of ordo, lex, medium − the mediological configuration of the
discipline? The initial answer, as adumbrated above, is that i
