AB  - Abstract This article focuses on one of the most recurrent motifs in
German Realism: law, and the ways in which its connection to themes of
observation and visibility suggests resonances with the activity of
theory, understood in its ancient Greek double sense of “seeing” as
well as “contemplating” (theoría). After briefly reconstructing the
ancient linkage between visibility, theoría, and law, the article
offers a close reading of two novellas by Gottfried Keller in which
this linkage occupies center stage: Romeo und Julia auf dem Dorfe
(1856/76) and Dietegen (1876). In both novellas, Keller shows the
operativity and validity of law to rest not so much within formal, de
iure institutions, but rather within its contingently de facto status
as an observable—i.e., theorizable—phenomenon that both arises from
and pertains to public viewership.
