AB  - This article elaborates on some iconographical and iconological
aspects of the late fifteenth century panel painting 'Dual Justice' by
local painter Jan van Brussel, today still in the Town Hall of
Maastricht (The Netherlands). The painting was commissioned by a
central jurisdiction council installed by burgundian duke Charles the
Bold. The painting, already commentated by Vanessa Paumen for the
catalogues of both the Bruges 'The Art of Law' and the Malines 'Call
for Justice' exhibitions, represents both the Last Judgment (upper
part) and a session of a court (lower part); both the devil and an
angel try to influence the court members. The article investigates
which court might be represented and what the particular roles of the
several court members is. It also explains why the angel is probably
the archangel Michael.
