AB  - Printed in 1559, Bruegel's 'Justicia' appears at first glance to be a
spatial representation of law—a snapshot, a mis en scene. But it is
essentially about time. Bruegel's image overlays three different
perspectives on the hitherto unexplored relationship between time,
responsibility, and legal authority, revealing the hidden anachronism
of law. At the same time, law is shown not merely to be a concept or a
symbolic form, but a physical practice engraved in the flesh of those
who carry it out and suffer it. Justicia takes as its method art's
anachronic discourse and power of embodiment; and presents as its
thesis the role of anachronic discourse and corporeal experience to
the law. These insights were pertinent to the situation of law in the
sixteenth century, but they are of far broader significance than that.
