AB  - In this introduction to a special volume celebrating the publication
of Judith Resnik’s and Denny Curtis’s book, Representing Justice:
Invention, Controversy, and Rights in City-States and Democratic
Courtrooms, I categorize material representations of justice as either
figural or architectural. Justice can be either "seen" or "sited," but
in either case there is a connection between these visual and physical
manifestations of justice and the desire of diverse governments to
signal political and judicial values. Resnik and Curtis teach us to
better understand the relationship between brick and mortar
instantiations of justice -- as well as the artwork adorning these
buildings -- and the architecture of procedural fairness and
adjudicative democracy. As a result we do, in fact, see things when we
look at a courthouse or a justice image that we may not have seen
previous to their timely intervention.
