AB  - This paper explores the role of images in (legal) philosophical
thought. It does so in two steps. The first step consists in
considering discussions of the role of images in philosophical
methodology, focusing especially on contemporary work by M. Le Doeuff
and M. La Caze, but drawing also on the ancient practice of philosophy
(as exemplified in Plato's dialogues). Philosophers often neglect how
often they use, and just how much they rely on, images: think only of
Plato's cave, Hegel's owl, Locke's tabula rasa, Wittgenstein's
language games, and Quine's web of belief. Such images immediately
bring to mind certain ideas and arguments, but also philosophical
temperaments. Having considered the role of images in philosophical
methodology, the second step consists in developing an account of
Zenon Bankowski's imaginary, i.e. the stock of images that appear in
his work, and examining the roles that those various images play.
These range from images of ATM machines that do not respond to the
particular person (but only ever the person represented in that
person’s card), and hence raise (by analogy) questions of the ethics
of legal judgement, to images of ‘bridging institutions’ that infuse
the legal system with ‘lay acid’, thereby renewing the law, preventing
it from becoming too isolated from the life of the community.
AU  - Mar, Del
