AB  - Abstract Among the many visual images we use for the law the garden is
an outstanding one. The topos of the garden has a wide semantic range:
it is the eternal metaphor of life and it is an ethical image
indicating the active behavioral rules man has to follow. The myth of
the garden arises connected to a structural system put at man’s
disposal, however a system which entails limits and limitations. The
action of shaping nature is connected with a sort of violence imposed
on nature: the garden becomes man’s grand scenario where man
challenges God in his ambition to modify and regulate nature. In the
case of both garden and law a creation according to certain rules is
implied and these rules must be respected unless the garden and the
juridical system wither and die. I here explore the relationship
between the concept of garden/landscape through which law is conceived
and from which it draws meaning.
