AB  - This article discusses the use of secular and Christian iconography
found in the important Jonsbok manuscript AM 350 fol., known
as Skarðsbok, from 1363. The case study concerns the text-image
relations of its illuminations and their form in terms of an
interpictuality, that is the changed patterns of iconography in the
context of a new textual frame. The study focuses on the symbolic
importance of the historical book painting and sets it into the
ideological background found in the polyphonic structure of the text.
The article aims to show that in AM 350 fol. we find not only a strong
Christian, holistic ideology visible in the interplay of text and
image, but also that previous ideas about its commisson and the
claimed intention of its production needs to be questioned.
