AB  - The following thesis debates the possibility of considering legal
institutes 1 as the central object of legal judgment. For such
purpose, I will critically approach the centrality of the concept of
norm, as well as that of a technical-normative judgment the jurist
works with, hence depending on a concept framework of a legal system
as a system of norms. In contrast and revisiting SAVIGNY'S thought, I
defend the thesis that legal institutes are the object of central
concern of law and jurisprudence from an aesthetic reflexive judgment
point of view, as defined by KANT in his third Critique. Therefore,
the institutes will be presented as icons, in terms of the
iconological school of WARBURG. To defend this point of view, an
allegory will be presented, which equates judgment in general with the
Greek daimon. Subsequently, the derivatives of an overall judgment
will be compared to the derivatives of the daimon itself, the
normative technical judgment to demons and the reflective judgment to
the genius.
