AB  - Over ten years ago now Peter Burke, an early-modern European
historian, wrote that ‘historians still do not take the evidence of
the image seriously enough’, leading others to speak of the
‘invisibility of the visual’ and the ‘condescension towards images’,
which this implies. ‘Relatively few historians’, he pointed out, ‘work
in photographic archives, compared to the numbers who work in
repositories of written and typewritten documents. Relatively few
historical journals carry illustrations and when they do, relatively
few contributors take advantage of this opportunity.’
