AB  - This article deals with the (legal) iconography and the popularity of
Peter Brueghel the Younger's well known 'Advocate of difficult
affairs' (Ghent Museum of Fine Arts). It is a satirical view on the
growing importance of the legal profession in the 16th-17th centuries.
The painting is compared to other early modern satirical
representations of the legal profession. The author also defends that
not actually a barrister ('advocaat'), but a 'proctor' is represented.
