AB  - Abstract The specific narratlvlty of pictures and its relation to the
narrativity of texts have increasingly gained attention in word and
image studies over the past few years.2 It has become clear that an
image that refers to a textual narrative does not have to be narrative
in character itself.3 Vice versa, narrative pictures may refer to
texts that have a low degree of narrativity.4 These latter cases are
particularly valuable for studying pictorial narrativity because the
images narrate stories ‘on their own’. That is why this article will
trace pictorial narrative in a medieval illuminated manuscript of the
German Sachsenspiegel (Saxon Mirror), a collection of customary laws.
Thc casc study hopes to open up new aspects for the study of this
manuscript as well as to contribute to the discussion concerning the
preconditions for a narrative picture.
