AB  - In medieval Danish wall paintings during the period 1100-1600, the evi
dence for depictions of jurisdiction which refer directly to the laws
and juridical institutions of the past society is rare. Instead, the
paintings contain a large number of scenes representing jurisdiction
with reference to Biblical stories. It is a tradition in medieval
imagery that Biblical persons are de picted in some kind of antique
clothing and settings. Consequently, the pri mary sign function—the
denotative level—performed by these motifs is not one of bringing
information about jurisdiction within society. Yet their ex tended
sign function—'la signification' (Barthes) or the connotative level-
does inform us of the notion of how justice could 'seem to be done'.
