AB  - Abstract This essay serves several critical and metacritical functions
in discussing the semiotic implications of the Chinese writing fa.
First of all, it examines critically various conceptualizations of "
image" in the current disciplines of " imagologies", and then it
comments on a contemporary French legal theoretician's image/mirage of
ancient Chinese civil law. After these surveys, the essay introduces a
highly specialized topic in legal semiotics by tracing the development
of the written sign of fa (law) in ancient China before the second
century BCE. The written word was interpreted to represent a mythical
animal, whose images have recurred in Chinese writing and art history.
Focusing on the scriptural representations of fa, this essay analyzes
the process of conceptualization of law in ancient China, and its
transformations and mutations across the borders of semiotic systems,
from the basic verbal and visual levels, to the higher levels of
ideology and legal theory and practice.
