Weigel develops a crucial critic of the anthropological paradigm
linked to the left-right problem in the visual arts. Focusing on
various examples of painted and sculpted Annunciations, the author
argues how the decline of the traditional orientation, based on the
figure of God in central position, leads to a growing importance of
the spectator gaze and to a new relation between iconic narration and
symbolic meaning.
