AB  - As a literary technique, allegory has a long tradition reaching back
to Antiquity. Its definition as extended metaphor by Quintilian is
just one aspect of a larger phenomenon that appears in different
media. The application of allegorical images can be observed on Roman
sarcophagi as well as on medieval walls and countless Renaissance
paintings. But what determines an allegory in the visual world? Almost
all theoretical approaches to allegory have texts in view. Since
allegory as a mode of seeing images has been discussed in different
ways, it is not clear to what extent allegory was a criterion for the
creation of images. Contemporaries of Giotto and of Ambrogio
Lorenzetti used different terms to describe paintings which are today
defined as allegorical. It is not until the 17th century that allegory
seems to be a category for texts as well as for images. During the
18th century, allegory suffered from the first signs of fatigue and
surfeit, but from a global perspective, the enhancement of visual
allegory can be observed in different contexts.
