TY  - CHAP
AB  - Political iconography refers to those medieval representations (both
text and image) that use traditional symbols to express some political
content. It is helpful to start my discussion of medieval political
iconography by introducing the emblematic way of seeing and thinking.
Since the subject of this essay is political iconography, it is
convenient to look at an emblematic example. In order to relate the
emblematic way of seeing and thinking to the medieval political
sphere, the authors would like to look at royal imagery and the
emergence of the political portrait. After that he will examine
heraldry as a semiotic system, the function of which was to highlight
political and social identities using a uniquely symbolic approach. In
the last part of my survey he shall look at civic political
iconography which emerged in Italy but soon became common all over the
continent.
AU  - Szönyi, György E.
