AB  - The magnificent illuminated manuscript of the Dresden "Sachsenspiegel"
was seriously damaged at the end of the Second World War. Having been
created in the Meissen area around 1350, it is one of four illuminated
manuscripts of the most significant legal text of the Middle Ages. The
text is illustrated throughout. The invaluable manuscript returned to
Dresden in 2000 after undergoing extensive restoration work at the
Herzog August Library in Wolfenbuttel. The "Sachsenspiegel", the
original version of which was recorded between 1220 and 1235 by Eike
von Repgow in the eastern foothills of the Harz mountains, spread to
many parts of Europe, most notably the eastern/central regions. Some
of its fundamental ideas continue to shape present-day laws.
AU  - Lück, H.
DA  - 2006///
PY  - 2006
ID  - temp_id_163342090541
TI  - Geschichtlichkeit und Aktualität der Dresdner Bilderhandschrift des
Sachsenspiegels
