AB  - The 18th century was marked by Parliaments’ will to affirm their
institutional prerogatives and political power with regard to the
king. Taking advantage of the difficulties the monarchy was
experiencing, in particular in the religious field with the sensitive
question of the Unigenitus bulla, parliamentarians opted for a logic
of systematic opposition to royal power. Beyond the traditional means
at their disposal, including remonstrances, strikes, and libel
actions, they developed a visual strategy based on a new type of
communication, which was essential to the process of entering the
public space. This paper highlights the implications of illustrations
during the parliamentary controversy during the reign of Louis XV
through images of justice and the elaboration of an autonomous
imaginary competing with that of the monarchy.
